For deciding whether any operation in OS_BinSemTimedWait is dead code we must know which operations have observable effects (return values, side‑effects, blocking, state changes). The following symbols are required and why:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The function gatekeeper — it is called unconditionally and determines whether the Impl call runs. Need its semantics (return codes) and whether it has observable side‑effects (e.g., registers events, modifies global state) so removal could change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These are the internal callees used by OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the call graph). If OS_ObjectIdGetById produces side effects via these routines (transactions, token conversion, array lookups), those side effects must be known to decide if the OS_ObjectIdGetById call is necessary or dead.
- OS_BinSemTimedWait_Impl: The body invoked when OS_ObjectIdGetById succeeds. Must know whether it performs observable actions (blocks, acquires/releases resources, signals, modifies global state). Removing this call would remove its effects — need its definition to determine if that would change program behaviour.
- OS_Posix_CompAbsDelayTime, OS_GenericBinSemTake_Impl: Immediate callees of OS_BinSemTimedWait_Impl (per the call graph). They may implement timing, blocking or other side effects; include them to understand the full observable behaviour of the Impl chain.
- OS_SUCCESS: The constant used to test the return of OS_ObjectIdGetById. Need its value/semantics to know which branch executes and whether the conditional is meaningful.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Constants passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById; they can alter OS_ObjectIdGetById behaviour (and thus whether subsequent code executes). Their meanings are required to reason about side effects.
- OS_object_token_t: The token type passed by address to OS_ObjectIdGetById and then to the Impl. Need its definition/semantics to determine whether its initialization/modification constitutes observable behaviour (MISRA note: initialization differs from assignment) and whether passing/ populating it has side effects.
- osal_id_t, int32, uint32: The parameter and return/value types used by the function. Required to interpret return semantics and whether integer widths/signedness influence observable behaviour (error codes, truncation, etc.).

With these symbols (the two direct calls plus their dependent internals, the constants that control behavior, and the involved types), an analyst can determine whether either call or any assignment/operation inside OS_BinSemTimedWait could be removed without changing program behaviour (i.e., whether it is dead code).
